# DTR: Define the Relationship

Use this template to when conducting DTR with your project partners. It's recommended that you copy/paste this template into your own gist each time you conduct a DTR to take notes on the conversation.

### Guiding Questions to Define The Relationship:

* What are your learning goals for this project?
Learn how to make a rails app that works, how to work with a larger group, how to manage a ton of user stories,
best practices for implementing, testing, and review.
What drives us in this project?
A desire to learn, getting things done, crushing those goals.
* What is your collaboration style? How do you feel about pair programming vs. divide-and-conquer approaches?
Divide and conquer together.
* How do you communicate best? How do you appreciate receiving communication from others?
Tim - In person, but will be available on slack. Honesty is the best policy. Open to feedback.
Autumn - In person, for constructive feedback. Be honest.
Ben - What Tim said.
Maria - Pretty open, coaching feedback asap, in person is best for feedback.
* How would you describe your work style?
Tim - Process the goods, wrap my head around it. Struggle a little before reaching out.
Autumn - Usually like to struggle through with self. Reaching out last option usually.
Ben - Likes to dive in and get hands dirty, wants to be more processy.
Maria - Process the goods, maybe reach out a little too late.
* What are your strengths?
Maria - Communication, testing, flexibility, problem solver, willing to learn
Autumn - Strategic, creative, testing, bootstrap, tables af
Tim - Learning, Strategic, high achiever sometimes
Ben - Attacks problems head on, maximizer, won't stop till I get enough
How can our strengths compliment each other?
Willingness to learn from each other, and other sources, flexibility to hear ideas and thoughts.
All gon git it.
* Whatâ€™s gone well or poorly in your previous projects?
Maria - In depth planning was very helpful, problems with commitment can ruin moral.
Tim - Waffle.io was a very helpful tool, problems with ideas not being communicated effectively.
Autumn - Walle.io fo sho was great, taking care of testing earlier than later is good, problem with not getting time to work how we work best.
Ben - Keeping a comfortable working speed is preferable, holding in my frustrations can lead to resentments.
* How will we set direction and make decisions as a team?
Thorough discussion, but the project manager watches us all.
* How will we overcome obstacles?
Regular Check-Ins
Together #CareBearStare
* What do you need (resources, environment, communication) to do your best work?
Autumn - Mentor time, solo time, less distractions the better, team availability, never NO COFFEE(caffeinated), some snacks.
Tim - Best work in afternoon/evening, time as a team, some solo time, snacks 4 dayz, regular check-ins
Maria - solo work team time, afternoon/evening best work, need quiet, access to team, ALWAYS COFFEE, snayucks, regular poms
Ben - Solo work/team time, relaxed environment, light music, regular poms, CAFFEINE, snacks.
* What scheduling restraints do you have? What are your scheduling preferences?
Weekends 10-4, STAY NO LATER THAN 8PM on weekdays.
Maria - Mentor, thursday/friday around 4:30.
Autumn - Mentor, tuesday evenings, weekend mornings.
* What is your style for giving feedback? Does anything ever hold you back from giving feedback?
All - Face to face, polite and actionable.
Tim - Hold back because they may not be open to it.
Autumn - Hold back in front of others.
Ben - Hold back because I may be a littttttttle heated, and don't wanna be snappy.
Maria - Hold back to spare the feelings of the victim.
* What tools do you want to use to manage the project?
waffle.io, PR Template, slack, GitHub
* How do you want the group to solve problems when members run into issues with features of the project?
Explain someone elses process, rubber ducking.
* How do you know if a project is successful? How can we achieve that as a group?
Get two's, and some three's, and not hate each other anymore than we do right now.
Through our strengths that we defined thrice above.
* How will we recognize each other's successes and celebrate them?
Regular encouragement, public praise, snack rewards.



Communicate clearly what you're working on.
Adopt similar topics, try to group by type.



### Template for DTR Memo

Project:

Group Member Names:

Project Expectations: What does each group member hope to get out of this project?

Goals and expectations:

Team strengths:

How to overcome obstacles:

Schedule Expectations (When are we available to work together and individually?):

Communication Expectations (How and often will we communicate? How do we keep lines of communication open?):

Abilities Expectations (Technical strengths and areas for desired improvement):

Workload Expectations (What features do we each want to work on?):

Workflow Expectations (Git workflow/Tools/Code Review/Reviewing Pull Requests):

Expectations for giving and receiving feedback:

Agenda to discuss project launch:

Ideas:

Tools:

Additional Notes:
